'''Robert Duncan James Shennan''' (born 18 March 1962, [[Wirral Urban District|Wirral]], [[Cheshire]], better known as '''Bob Shennan''') is a British radio executive who was appointed as Controller of [[BBC Radio 2]] and [[BBC Radio 6 Music]] in January 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7853040.stm|title= Shennan becomes head of Radio 2|publisher= BBC Online|date= 27 January 2009|accessdate= 30 January 2009}}</ref>

==Early life==
He was educated at [[Lancaster Royal Grammar School]] and [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]].

==Career==
Shennan has been a senior executive in radio and television for a number of years. He started as a journalist at [[102.7 Heart Peterborough|Hereward Radio]] in [[Peterborough]] from 1984-7. He joined BBC Sport in 1987 as a trainee radio sport producer and was part of the team that founded [[BBC Radio Five Live]].<ref>{{Cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/726042.stm|title= New boss for 5Live|publisher= BBC Online|date= 25 April 2000|accessdate= 11 February 2009}}</ref> After a spell as Head of [[BBC Sport]] where he had overall responsibility for sports coverage on BBC radio and television, he was appointed head of [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] in 2000.<ref name="BBC press">{{Cite web|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2009/01_january/27/shennan.shtml|title= Bob Shennan appointed Controller BBC Radio 2 and BBC 6 Music|publisher= BBC Online|date= 27 January 2009|accessdate= 30 January 2009}}</ref> As the network's controller he oversaw the launch of [[BBC Radio Five Live Sports Extra]] in 2002, and also took over as controller of the [[BBC Asian Network]] in 2004.

===Channel 4===
In December 2007 it was announced that Shennan would be leaving the BBC to take up a position as Director of Radio at [[Channel Four]].<ref name="Leaving">{{Cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7125641.stm|title= BBC's 5 Live boss quits for rival|publisher= BBC Online|date= 3 December 2007|accessdate= 11 February 2009}}</ref> He joined the broadcaster in April 2008 as it made plans to diversify into radio with the launch of several stations under the banner of [[Channel Four Radio]].<ref name="BBC press"/><ref name="Leaving"/> However, in October 2008 Channel Four shelved its radio project in order to make a reported <U+00A3>100million in savings.<ref name="Guardian">{{Cite news|url= http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2009/jan/27/bob-shennan-named-radio-2-controller|title= Bob Shennan named Radio 2 controller|publisher= Guardian Media|date= 27 January 2009|accessdate= 30 January 2009 | location=London | first=Leigh | last=Holmwood}}</ref>

===Radio 2===
Shennan took over in February 2009 from [[Lesley Douglas]], who resigned from her position following the [[Russell Brand Show prank telephone calls row]].<ref name="Guardian"/> He is regarded as a "safe pair of hands" for the network following the controversy.<ref name="Guardian"/>

{{s-start}}
{{incumbent succession box|title=[[BBC Radio 2|Controller, BBC Radio 2]]|before=[[Lesley Douglas]]|start=2009}}
{{s-end}}

He is also Chair, Fellow and Trustee of the [[Radio Academy]].<ref name="BBC press"/><ref>The Radio Academy [http://www.radioacademy.org/about/fellows/ "Fellows"]</ref>

==Personal life==
He married Joanne Margaret Melford in July 1987 in Lancaster. They have two sons (born January 1992 and March 1996) and one daughter (born August 1993).

